          "type": "text",
          "text": "Circuit built successfully! Here's the full breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## 🔢 7-Segment Counter Circuit\n\n### Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Connected To | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| **D2** | R_a → Segment **a** | Top bar |\n| **D3** | R_b → Segment **b** | Top-right bar |\n| **D4** | R_c → Segment **c** | Bottom-right bar |\n| **D5** | R_d → Segment **d** | Bottom bar |\n| **D6** | R_e → Segment **e** | Bottom-left bar |\n| **D7** | R_f → Segment **f** | Top-left bar |\n| **D8** | R_g → Segment **g** | Middle bar |\n| **D9** | Button (+ INPUT_PULLUP) | Count trigger |\n| **GND** | 7-seg common cathode | Display ground |\n| **GND** | Button other leg | Button ground |\n\nEach segment pin is protected by a **220Ω resistor**.\n\n---\n\n### How It Works\n1. **Button pressed** → D9 reads LOW (active-low with internal pull-up)\n2. **Debounce** (50ms) prevents false triggers from mechanical bounce\n3. **Counter increments** 0 → 1 → 2 → ... → 9 → **back to 0**\n4. The `showDigit()` function drives the 7 segment pins with the correct ON/OFF pattern for each digit\n\n---\n\n### ⚡ Power Budget Summary\n\n| Item | Current | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Each lit segment | ~14mA | (5V − 2V) / 220Ω ≈ 13.6mA |\n| Max segments on (digit **8**) | ~95mA total | All 7 segments ON |\n| Typical digit (avg ~4 segs) | ~55mA | Within Uno 5V rail limit |\n| Button pin | <1mA | Pull-up only, no load |\n| **Per Arduino pin** | ≤14mA | ✅ Under 20mA limit |\n| **Total board draw** | ~55–95mA | ✅ Uno 5V rail can handle ~500mA |\n\n> ✅ All per-pin currents stay well below the 20mA safety limit. The 220Ω resistors are doing their job!"
        }
